{"hits": {"hits": [{"created": "2026-04-20T18:49:29.794154+00:00", "modified": "2026-04-22T16:02:57.355401+00:00", "id": 19669145, "conceptrecid": "19669144", "doi": "10.5281/zenodo.19669145", "conceptdoi": "10.5281/zenodo.19669144", "doi_url": "https://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.19669145", "metadata": {"title": "Analysis of Alternative Captive Bat Management Strategies in  Response to White-nose Syndrome", "doi": "10.5281/zenodo.19669145", "publication_date": "2014", "description": "(Uploaded by Plazi for the Bat Literature Project) This report describes the process and presents the results of a structured decision making effort 29 that was initiated by the U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service in November 2010. This initiative 30 addressed the potential efficacy of captive bat management to as one means of addressing white31 nose syndrome for seven species of concern. This was done by comparing alternative 32 management strategies against identified objectives, and by comparing captive management 33 against no captive management. Expert elicitation was used to conduct the analyses, which 34 concluded in 2012. Afterwards, the team of U.S. Fish and Wildlife biologists that was convened 35 for the decision making effort reviewed results, made recommendations, and prepared this draft 36 report. 37 38 Although the results and recommendations have been presented to U.S. Fish and Wildlife 39 decision makers, this draft report has not been approved by agency officials nor does it represent 40 an official agency position. When approved, it will be considered a white paper rather than a 41 decision document. Further, certain results and recommendations may need to be revisited. The 42 analyses were conducted with a 5-year time frame in mind, and reconsideration of the status of 43 the bats with regard to white-nose syndrome could result in modification of the decision 44 framework that was developed for the initiative and/or inputs into the decision framework that 45 was developed for the initiative. Updating is thus an integral aspect of the decision framework, 46 which should remain relevant as long as questions regarding captive management as a possible 47 response to the impacts of white-nose syndrome on insectivorous bats remain.", "access_right": "restricted", "creators": [{"name": "Parkin, Mary", "affiliation": null}, {"name": "Tawes, Robert", "affiliation": null}, {"name": "Pruitt, Lori", "affiliation": null}, {"name": "Rayman, Noelle", "affiliation": null}, {"name": "Stark, Richard", "affiliation": null}, {"name": "Niver, Robyn", "affiliation": null}, {"name": "Von Oettingen, Susi", "affiliation": null}, {"name": "Douglas, Barbara", "affiliation": null}, {"name": "McKenzie, Paul", "affiliation": null}, {"name": "Coleman, Jeremy", "affiliation": null}, {"name": "Valenta, Aaron", "affiliation": null}], "keywords": ["Biodiversity", "Mammalia", "Chiroptera", "Chordata", "Animalia", "bats", "bat"], "related_identifiers": [{"identifier": "hash://md5/0b1ac275ee80365143083d99f000cab1", "relation": "hasVersion", "scheme": "url"}, {"identifier": "hash://sha256/0864351eb30d866be6637205cc843aaa1a1ab59d317e8394cd3d6e2e1a6c82f9", "relation": "hasVersion", "scheme": "url"}, {"identifier": "zotero://select/groups/5435545/items/SFBWD2KR", "relation": "isDerivedFrom", "scheme": "url"}, {"identifier": "https://zotero.org/groups/5435545/items/SFBWD2KR", "relation": "isDerivedFrom", "scheme": "url"}, {"identifier": "https://linker.bio/cut:hash://md5/c7f1cf817322f72fe893c6a60f1b98a4!/b319553-322028", "relation": "isDerivedFrom", "scheme": "url"}, {"identifier": "hash://md5/0157e8ec3f1f8eb877e7b6cd6fde26bc", "relation": "isPartOf", "scheme": "url"}, {"identifier": "10.5281/zenodo.1410543", "relation": "isCompiledBy", "resource_type": "software", "scheme": "doi"}], "custom": {"dwc:class": ["Mammalia"], "dwc:kingdom": ["Animalia"], "dwc:order": ["Chiroptera"], "dwc:phylum": ["Chordata"]}, "resource_type": {"title": "Preprint", "type": "publication", "subtype": 